SIMPLE: rip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rip
<hw>Rip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>hrip</ets>
a box or basket; perhaps akin to E. <ets>corb</ets>. Cf.
<er>Ripier</er>.]</ety> <def>A wicker fish basket.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rip
<hw>Rip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ripped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ripping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>r⟦ymac⟧pan</ets>,
also Sw. <ets>repa</ets> to ripple flax, D. <ets>repelen</ets>, G.
<ets>reffen</ets>, <ets>riffeln</ets>, and E. <ets>raff</ets>,
<ets>raffle</ets>. Cf. <er>Raff</er>, <er>Ripple</er> of flax.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To divide or separate the parts of, by cutting or
tearing; to tear or cut open or off; to tear off or out by violence;
<as>as, to <ex>rip</ex> a garment by cutting the stitches; to
<ex>rip</ex> off the skin of a beast; to <ex>rip</ex> up a floor</as>;
-- commonly used with <xex>up</xex>, <xex>open</xex>,
<xex>off</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To get by, or as by, cutting or tearing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He 'll <qex>rip</qex> the fatal secret from her heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Granville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To tear up for search or disclosure, or for
alteration; to search to the bottom; to discover; to disclose; --
usually with <xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>ripped</qex> up all that had been done from the
beginning of the rebellion.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For brethern to debate and <qex>rip</qex> up their falling out in
the ear of a common enemy . . . is neither wise nor comely.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To saw (wood) lengthwise of the grain or
fiber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ripping chisel</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>a
crooked chisel for cleaning out mortises.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> --
<col><b>Ripping iron</b></col>. <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Ravehook</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ripping saw</b></col>.
<fld>(Carp.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Ripsaw</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To rip
out</b></col>, <cd>to rap out, to utter hastily and violently; as,
<xex>to rip out</xex> an oath.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <see>See
<cref>To rap out</cref>, under <er>Rap</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos></see></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rip
<hw>Rip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A rent made by ripping,
esp. by a seam giving way; a tear; a place torn; laceration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Perh. a corruption of the first syllable of
<ets>rep</ets>robate.]</ety> <def>A term applied to a mean, worthless
thing or person, as to a scamp, a debauchee, or a prostitute, or a
worn-out horse.</def> <mark>[Slang.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A body of water made rough by the meeting of
opposing tides or currents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Riparian</ent>⟦br⟧
